title: Grateful Dead Live at Public Hall on 1973-12-06
description: Set 1 Bertha, Mexicali Blues, Loser, Black Throated Wind, They Love Each Other, Beat It On Down The Line, Deal, El Paso, Row Jimmy, Greatest Story Ever Told, China Cat Sunflower > I Know You Rider, Around And Around Set 2 Ramble On Rose, Me And My Uncle, Here Comes Sunshine, Big River, Dark Star-> Eyes Of The World> Stella Blue, Sugar Magnolia 2nd set includes the longest ever Here Comes Sunshine (15'38) and the 3rd longest ever Dark Star (43'28) updated venue and setlist courtesy Deadlists

reviews.review_text:
Thanks so much great  set 2!!!
one of the best

Here Comes Sunshine Patched! Thanks, Charlie Miller, for finally fixing the ugly patch at the end of one of the finest (if not the finest) version of Here Comes Sunshine ever played! I skipped right to that part when I saw this on the TJI list. This show is amazing! One of my favorites from '73.

Listmaker! This is a Top 10 on my heart & soul list.

Thanks, All.

The sun will shine in my back door--someday! Set One
Bertha, Mexicali Blues, Loser, Black Throated Wind, They Love Each Other, Beat It On Down The Line, Deal, El Paso, Row Jimmy, Greatest Story Ever Told, China Cat Sunflower > I Know You Rider, Around And Around

I am just up to the China >Rider and words just can't do justice to how hot this show is.
Hearing Phil's bass echo in my headphones at the end of RIDER. 
Not a big fan of AROUND but it sizzles too!

I dig every single tune here, and there is just that extra effort, attention to detail, moxy!!!
There is nothing needed to be added and nothing needs to be taken away.

Set Two
Ramble on Rose-Jerry singing directly down the mic- right in my ear, "Take you to the leader of the band"
Me & My Uncle-"I left his dead ass there by the side of the road"
Bob and Phil have running commentary going all night 'Venutian Red Cross'
Bob- "Donna home getting big and round"
Here Comes Sunshine= [This tune helped me down   so many roads. They weren't Playin' it live for most of the time when I was going to shows.]
They are already so loose and this is the 1st exploration tune of the night. 
They are just going for it. I hear the main theme and just Jerry wailing away. Phil smoldering along side him. Weir adding Rhythm. If you can track with this you get the Dead. Here it is! 
Big River-Not an obvious choice , but whatever they play is going to be good. Keith sounding nice on Piano. Billy beats his drum kit to death on this tune. "going to sit right here till I die"
Dark Star> they drift gently into this STAR
15 minutes in and I am pretty sure I haven't heard the bass line for the Dark Star just yet?
What a jam, Phil is just like a fuzz tone of sound. Jerry playin' a sweet little melody in the midst of it all. This is somewhat dissonant. Hand in a light socket sound. GOD help the tripping fool tonight.
Wow, that is over the top a 20 minute intro to the STAR! another 5 minutes for the verse.
This is a pretty challenging Dark Star it is in the vein of SUN RA. I am a little surprised after they nailed all those beautiful tunes that they get so heavy here. It really was not what I was expecting at all. Now they are heading back into a more structured mode closing in on the EYES. But still pretty atonal and dissonant. Just waiting to see how they get this to EYES.
Pretty cool transition almost thought they might go for CHINA DOll. EYES is an excellent choice because that was a hairy jam in the Dark Star.
Jerry just sounds so fine singing here!
And they are back into Sunshine and blue skies!!!
"The night comes so quiet and it is close on the heels of the day"
The jam in EYES is good and bouncing in every which direction, almost sounded like they might come back for the Dark Star
And it is going to be Stella Blue for a Jerry ballad.(Could use some Donna Jean oh's & ah's)
Donna not here is a plus in that the band can stretch out some and it makes everyone else step up to sing backing vocals but it also is a minus like when the boys forget to keep straight the chorus Beaches-Heart-thoughts and then Seasons-Evening-Songs --Donna always keeps those right.
Recap-This show has something for everybody and then some. Still freakin on that Dark Star. This is like two shows everything before and after STAR and then the STAR itself.
Sugar Magnolia!

"LRY?," Phil asks http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liberal_Religious_Youth

"...Notable LRYers

    Carolyn Garcia (aka Mountain Girl, aka Carolyn Adams) – Merry Prankster and the wife of Jerry Garcia of The Grateful Dead.[4]..."

Stars - No Stars If this Dark Star doesn't equal where you're at today, try it again tomorrow, or the next time you're stuck in Cleveland. Even though captured, the music is not frozen. 
C-Freedom - nice SunRa reference, but this type of DS sometimes reminds me of Wayne Shorter's "Odyssey of Iska" from 1971.
And speaking of Weather Report, Does anyone else notice a sonic resemblance between Phil's early 70's sound and that of Miroslav Vitous' electric playing of the same era?

time capsule Thanks to the good souls who made this one available.  I was lucky enough to attend this show so it's a wonderful bit of nostalgia to sit back now, some forty years later, and hear it all again.  Esp. this DS.  As you can imagine, it was a hair-raising experience live (literally) so having a chance to hear it again is quite a treat.  It is much more complex musically than I realized at the time.  Really, the whole show is like that, very complex.

In that way, this soundboard is a reminder of how valuable these recordings are historically.  No one is playing music like this anymore.

Here Comes Sunshine 4-2-1973 has the longest Here Comes Sunshine at about 20 minutes long, going into some really deep dark spacey stuff. People that don't enjoy the weirdness cut HCS into 2 tracks labeled as HereComesSunshine>JAM, they did this so they could skip to the next song once it got to be "too much". Most the track timings here on the archive are off, one has to listen to the track to actually know when the song starts and ends and what is "dead air". Also most if not all tracks listed as "Space" that come from shows prior to around 1979, are actually just part of jams that people don't enjoy and want the option of skipping. 

This 12/06 show is awesome, look to some of the past reviews on a couple of the older sources for some in depth song breakdowns etc.

Nitpicks Not the biggest deal, but even though this is an upgrade (which I do recognize and GREATLY appreciate), it seems odd to me that in contrast with the other Miller SBD of this show (https://archive.org/details/gd1973-12-06.sbd.miller.105560.flac16/gd73-12-06d3t01.flac), this is one is missing the first 20 seconds of Dark Star. Again, not a huge issue (especially cause of the longer tunings between songs), but I still wonder why...

Hello Cleveland
This is part of the Donna-less tour that includes the Tampa shows, the great Boston shows and the fantastic Charlotte show. It's tough to measure against those, however this show has long received historical notoriety for the lengthy Here Comes Sunshine, and the divisive, long-debated Dark Star (probably more so than 10/26/89). You'll probably listen for those reasons too. There don't seem to be any AUDs floating around but I swear a partial has circulated for a long time. Maybe it was a partial SBD, well-degenerated, that I recall from the B&P days. We all got the mostly-whole show in 2004; a more complete show in 2009. A pitch-corrected, mastered version appeared in 2010, and the most-complete version in 2015. Meanwhile in 2011 there was an official partial release. First Set. The first few seconds of this tentative Bertha are missing on all sources. The next few songs are average, but by Black Throated it's become sort of a flat set. A solid They Love Each Other is a nice spark, but Beat it on Down the Line-5 is meh (5 on the 6th?). Phil mentions Comet Kohoutek, and if you are old enough, you'll recall that it was a huge deal, partially because back then we had much less warning about NEOs, and because it was erroneously over-estimated by the press (the Hale-Bopp was better). Most of this set is just GOGD - what they sound like on a given night in '73. Greatest Story seems pretty average too - until Jer outgasses a great jam into orbit. Though Bobby has a tough time of it, the ace of the set. The China>Rider is mostly pretty good. It's not 11/17, but does have a gauzy Feelin' Groovy jam. Around is just a little off; but the 1st set alone is like an entire concert. Second Set. Ramble is propitious after the first set, and Me & My Uncle is a true gel. This Here Comes Sunshine is oft-discussed as an historical version. At 16min, it may be the 2nd longest ever (cf 4/2). It's good, even if not the best of '73 (or the tour; cf 11/17, 11/30, 12/19). Big River is just an absolutely superb, boogie version, and the strongest statement of the show. Slightly withered from that Dark Star, Eyes is good - heck aren't all Eyes good in '73? But this is less tentative than most of the show, the 2nd solo is magical, and there's a nice breakdown section. Weirdly, I "got it" after 4 times through (considering that the boys only played it once!). However, at this point Bobby's fading guitar now mostly leaves the mix, and that makes listening challenging. The rest is too tentative (as others have noted). The Dark Star>Eyes>Stella sequence is 66mins. Why is some tripper begging Jer for water? The next jam (Sugar Mag) is okay, but not great sans Bobby's guitar, and his hoarse screaming precludes an encore. This is a "Phil Show", but without much energy from everyone else except Keith, who drives in places. The wide variety of opinions about the Dark Star (and the show) are wonderful. But it's too bad about the missing Bobby guitar. The Dark Star. This is the third-longest, if you include 4/24/72, which has a M&MU in the middle (of an all-time best). It gels out of a tuning, and @2:10 Keith moves from his Steinway to his Rhodes. I think only 9/27/72 is longer pre-lyrics (@24½mins). You can read hundreds of comments for/against this one, so you can only take the journey and decide. The Kaplan source has the complete tuning intro (you can't discern where the tuning ends, so...). The reason it's so long is because it isn't a Dark Star for about a week; it's just a loose jam until the theme is stated (okay, it's @21min). There's a lot of feedback-playing, clanging, extremely loose & non-musical meanderings; everything Dead haters profess is right here. As for those of us who ARE cool, it's just going to be a divider. There are great sections in just about any Dark Star, but there is not much here that's memorable until the last 6mins. Of course there's the length=quality camp; their lives patently enviable for their ease. That said, there is something to be said for the way it just appears from formlessness...and then stays there. Check 2/2 & 10/19 for actual playing! But, quoting Old_NJ_Head_Zimmer, "remarkable not only for its scale but for its structure, which turns the Third Stage inside-out, working in toward the theme, rather than starting from it, and moving out into space after the 1st vox, rather than back from it". TL;DR > I'm in the once-is-enough camp. 1st Set:  C 2nd Set: B- Overall = 3 Stars Highlights: You are here to tackle it, no matter what I think! SOURCES: The 132361_sbd_miller is an upgrade of the miller_105560, but that one has the extra 15sec tuning-intro to Dark Star (as does the kaplan-fink-hamilton_4452, which has an incomplete HCS). Greatest Story, China>Rider, the complete Dark Star and Eyes are on the bonus disc of Road Trips 4-3.
Great 'Here comes...' Loving the Sunshine of course, and immediately noticed its length.  And thank you (previous commentor) for the historical reference on the Dark Star here.
